      "text": "A 10-year-old child was brought to the emergency department after consuming a significant quantity of iron tablets at home. The child is presenting with severe abdominal pain, profuse gastrointestinal bleeding episodes, and lethargy. What is the preferred treatment for this case?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Pencillamine"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "BAL"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Activated charcoal"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Deferoxamine Mesylate"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Option D - </strong>Deferoxamine Mesylate</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>This is the correct answer. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"423bba3d10169277718536aa18aea0\">Deferoxamine</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5f526a682c16927771923e095d017e\">Mesylate</span> is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f4305306cd16927771847a63caf4c7\">chelating agent</span> specifically used to treat iron poisoning. It forms a complex with iron, which is then excreted through the urine. Iron <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"072b8af16e1692777196f21b086f92\">poisoning</span> can lead to severe complications, such as <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b3a647ce2516927771881427f56c1d\">gastrointestinal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"41e858bf2816927771836d46c619b9\">bleeding</span> and organ damage, so prompt and effective treatment with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"423bba3d10169277718536aa18aea0\">Deferoxamine</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5f526a682c16927771923e095d017e\">Mesylate</span> is essential.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Incorrect Options:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Option A - Pencillamine: </strong>Penicillamine is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f4305306cd16927771847a63caf4c7\">chelating agent</span> primarily used to treat Wilson's disease and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"40dbde72e41692777197e59d893839\">rheumatoid</span> arthritis. It is not the preferred treatment for iron poisoning.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option B - <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"eff14f005f16927771826bf88cb6c5\">BAL</span> (British Anti-Lewisite or Dimercaprol): </strong>BAL is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f4305306cd16927771847a63caf4c7\">chelating agent</span> used to treat <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6e8ada09fa1692777189bfbace851a\">heavy metal</span> poisoning, such as lead and arsenic poisoning. It is not the preferred treatment for iron poisoning.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option C - Activated charcoal: </strong>Activated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e7626b047e169277718484971217b8\">charcoal</span> is used to absorb certain toxins in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b3a647ce2516927771881427f56c1d\">gastrointestinal</span> tract. However, in the case of iron poisoning, it is not effective because iron tablets have already been absorbed and are causing <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8f2e7fd96116927771995b451b5c90\">systemic</span> effects.</p>",
